            <section class="prose">
              <h2>How this student loan calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This student loan calculator uses standard amortization math to
                estimate your monthly payment, total interest, and payoff time.
                It also models how interest may accrue during an in-school or
                grace period for unsubsidized loans.
              </p>

              <h3>1. Interest during school / grace period</h3>
              <p>
                For <strong>unsubsidized loans</strong>, interest typically
                accrues while you are in school and during your grace period. If
                you do not pay it as it accrues, it is usually
                <strong>capitalized</strong> (added to your principal) when
                repayment begins.
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">
                  Interest accrued during grace period
                </p>
                <p>
                  Monthly rate: \( r_m = \dfrac{r}{12} \)<br />
                  Months in grace: \( n_g \)<br />
                  Accrued interest (simple approximation):<br />
                  \( I_{\text{grace}} \approx P \times r_m \times n_g \)
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                The calculator adds this accrued interest to your original
                principal to get the
                <strong>repayment starting balance</strong>. For subsidized
                loans, we assume no interest accrues during the grace period.
              </p>

              <h3>2. Monthly payment formula</h3>
              <p>
                Once repayment starts, the loan is treated as a standard
                fixed-payment installment loan. The monthly payment is
                calculated using the standard amortization formula:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">Fixed monthly payment</p>
                <p>
                  Let:<br />
                  \( P_0 \) = balance at repayment start (after any
                  capitalization)<br />
                  \( r_m \) = monthly interest rate = APR / 12<br />
                  \( n \) = total number of payments = years × 12<br /><br />
                  Then the monthly payment \( M \) is:<br />
                  \( M = P_0 \times \dfrac{r_m (1 + r_m)^n}{(1 + r_m)^n - 1} \)
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                Total repaid is \( M \times n \). Total interest is total repaid
                minus the original principal you borrowed.
              </p>

              <h3>3. Extra payment calculations</h3>
              <p>
                When you add a fixed extra monthly payment, the calculator
                simulates the amortization month by month:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Each month, interest = current balance × monthly rate.</li>
                <li>Payment = standard payment + extra payment.</li>
                <li>
                  Principal reduction = payment − interest (but never less than
                  zero).
                </li>
                <li>Balance is reduced until it reaches zero.</li>
              </ul>
              <p>From this simulation, we compute:</p>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>New payoff time</strong> (in years and months).</li>
                <li><strong>Total interest with extra payments</strong>.</li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Interest saved</strong> and
                  <strong>time saved</strong> vs. the standard plan.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>How to interpret your student loan results</h2>
              <h3>Monthly payment</h3>
              <p>
                This is the fixed amount you would pay each month under a
                standard repayment plan with the term you selected. It does not
                include potential fees or changes from income-driven repayment
                plans.
              </p>

              <h3>Total interest</h3>
              <p>
                Total interest shows how much you pay the lender for borrowing
                the money, on top of the amount you originally borrowed. Longer
                terms lower your monthly payment but increase total interest.
              </p>

              <h3>Capitalized interest</h3>
              <p>
                Capitalized interest is interest that accrues during school or
                grace and is added to your principal. Paying at least the
                interest during this period can significantly reduce your total
                cost.
              </p>

              <h2>Strategies to manage student loan debt</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Compare terms before borrowing:</strong> Shorter terms
                  mean higher payments but much less interest.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Pay interest while in school:</strong> Especially on
                  unsubsidized loans, this prevents capitalization.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Make small extra payments:</strong> Even $25–$50 extra
                  per month can save hundreds or thousands in interest.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Refinance carefully:</strong> Private refinancing may
                  lower your rate but can remove federal protections and
                  forgiveness options.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Use official tools for IDR:</strong> For income-driven
                  repayment, always rely on your servicer or government
                  calculators.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <p class="text-xs text-gray-500">
                Disclaimer: This calculator is for educational purposes only and
                does not provide legal, financial, or tax advice. Actual payment
                amounts and terms depend on your lender, loan servicer, and
                applicable regulations.
              </p>

              <h2>Student loan calculator FAQ</h2>

              <h3>How do I calculate my monthly student loan payment?</h3>
              <p>
                Enter your loan amount, interest rate, and repayment term. The
